{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"13674dce-bb7c-490c-88d1-e974d82658e3","content":"The best approach is **`dotnet-trace`** with the CPU profiling profile. From inside the pod:\n\n```bash\n# Install the tool (if not already present)\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\n\n# Find your app's PID\ndotnet-trace ps\n\n# Collect a 30-second CPU trace\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\nThis produces a `.nettrace` file you can analyze in **Visual Studio**, **PerfView**, or **Speedscope** (export with `--format speedscope`).\n\n**Tips:**\n- If you can't install tools in the container, use a **sidecar** or `kubectl cp` a self-contained `dotnet-trace` binary in.\n- For production-safe, lower-overhead collection, consider `dotnet-counters` first to confirm the CPU source, then trace.\n- Use `--providers Microsoft-DotNETCore-SampleProfiler` if you want just the sampled CPU stacks with minimal overhead.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"45abe8c7-89d2-4dd7-b070-f97abb37494c","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app running in a Kubernetes pod on Linux. This is a knowledge question, not a code change request, so I'll provide a concise answer.","outputTokens":314},"id":"97a24213-714e-4406-add3-b5448876e022","timestamp":"2026-04-05T00:53:33.994Z","parentId":"d8b88551-1d09-44c8-bd6b-21d56c11d504"}
